1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,400
We've just covered Boolean operators.

2

00:00:02,400  -->  00:00:07,760
Now let's dive into another important set of operators called relational operators.

3

00:00:07,760  -->  00:00:12,060
These operators compare values and return true or false.

4

00:00:12,060  -->  00:00:16,840
They are often used in Boolean expressions to help us make decisions in our code.

5

00:00:16,840  -->  00:00:22,900
Let's explore each one of these new operators with an example of it in action.

6

00:00:22,900  -->  00:00:27,500
The equal to operator checks if two values are equal.

7

00:00:27,500  -->  00:00:29,720
If they are, it returns true.

8

00:00:29,720  -->  00:00:32,360
Otherwise, it returns false.

9

00:00:32,360  -->  00:00:37,320
In this example, a and b both hold the value five,

10

00:00:37,320  -->  00:00:41,805
so a == b evaluates to true.

11

00:00:41,805  -->  00:00:46,330
The not equal to operator checks if two values are not equal.

12

00:00:46,330  -->  00:00:49,090
If they are not equal, it returns true.

13

00:00:49,090  -->  00:00:51,275
Otherwise, it returns false.

14

00:00:51,275  -->  00:00:53,685
Here, a is five,

15

00:00:53,685  -->  00:00:55,485
and b is three,

16

00:00:55,485  -->  00:01:00,120
so a does not equal b.

17

00:01:00,120  -->  00:01:02,385
Here, a is five,

18

00:01:02,385  -->  00:01:03,750
and b is three,

19

00:01:03,750  -->  00:01:11,230
so a!= b evaluates to true because they are different values.

20

00:01:11,230  -->  00:01:13,670
The greater than operator checks if

21

00:01:13,670  -->  00:01:17,470
a value on the left is greater than the value on the right.

22

00:01:17,470  -->  00:01:19,800
If it is, it returns true.

23

00:01:19,800  -->  00:01:22,245
Otherwise, it returns false.

24

00:01:22,245  -->  00:01:24,930
In this example, a is greater than b,

25

00:01:24,930  -->  00:01:28,810
so a > b evaluates to true.

26

00:01:28,810  -->  00:01:31,810
The greater than or equal to operator checks if

27

00:01:31,810  -->  00:01:35,690
the value on the left is greater than or equal to the value on the right.

28

00:01:35,690  -->  00:01:37,630
If it is, it returns true,

29

00:01:37,630  -->  00:01:39,970
otherwise, it returns false.

30

00:01:39,970  -->  00:01:43,095
Here, a is equal to b,

31

00:01:43,095  -->  00:01:47,385
so a >= b evaluates to true.

32

00:01:47,385  -->  00:01:50,020
The less than operator checks if the value

33

00:01:50,020  -->  00:01:52,740
on the left is less than the value on the right.

34

00:01:52,740  -->  00:01:54,880
If it is, it returns true.

35

00:01:54,880  -->  00:01:57,060
Otherwise, it returns false.

36

00:01:57,060  -->  00:02:00,300
In this example, a is less than b,

37

00:02:00,300  -->  00:02:03,975
so a < b evaluates to true.

38

00:02:03,975  -->  00:02:07,520
The less than or equal to operator checks if the value on

39

00:02:07,520  -->  00:02:11,420
the left is less than or equal to the value on the right.

40

00:02:11,420  -->  00:02:13,520
If it is, it returns true.

41

00:02:13,520  -->  00:02:15,740
Otherwise, it returns false.

42

00:02:15,740  -->  00:02:18,030
Here, a is equal to b,

43

00:02:18,030  -->  00:02:22,225
so a <= b evaluates to true.

44

00:02:22,225  -->  00:02:25,340
Congrats, you've just learned a whole new set

45

00:02:25,340  -->  00:02:28,260
of tools for relational operations in Python.

46

00:02:28,260  -->  00:02:31,060
These operators are fundamental

47

00:02:31,060  -->  00:02:34,420
in programming and will help you control the flow of your code.

48

00:02:34,420  -->  00:02:39,500
Great work and keep it going as we move into the next video ahead.
